on in action.\n\n3. Millennium Development Goals\n\nThe Millennium Development Goals (MDGs), the United Nations' blueprint to tackle a number of global problems by a target date of 2015, included several health-related issues. This graphic, also created by the IHME, includes extensive data on child mortality, maternal mortality, the spread of HIV and AIDS, malaria and tuberculosis.\n\nClick here to see the full interactive.\n\n4. New HIV diagnoses\n\nHIVContinuum is an interactive map from AIDSVu, a project based at the Rollins School of Public Health at Emory University. It shows new HIV diagnoses, late HIV diagnoses, linkage and engagement to HIV care, and more.\n\nUsers can look at city-specific data for Atlanta, Chicago, New Orleans, Philadelphia and Washington, D.C., and also filter by sex, race and ethnicity, and age.\n\n5. Vaccine-preventable outbreaks\n\nLoading...\n\nAs the measles outbreak linked to Disneyland began to spread in January 2015, a heated debate resurged surrounding the importance of vaccinations.\n\nThe Global Health Program at the Council on Foreign Relations created this data visualization, which plots global outbreaks of measles, mumps, whooping cough, polio, rubella and other preventable diseases.\n\nTo see the larger version, click here. \n\n6. Overweight and obesity patterns\n\nThe IHME released this interactive graphic in May 2014, highlighting global overweight and obesity prevalence in adults between 1980 and 2013. The data comes from a variety of surveys, reports and published studies.\n\nUsers can filter data by body mass index (BMI), age (20 years old and above), sex and location. See the full interactive visualization here.\n\n7. Malnutrition and other public health problems\n\n   \n\nThe International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI) released its first-ever annual Global Nutrition Report, a comprehensive analysis on the state of the world's nutrition, in November 2014. This data visualization uses information from the report, illustrating several types of widespread malnutrition around the world.\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"facebook":169,"twitter":1495,"pinterest":8,"google_plus":21,"stumble_upon":68,"total":1761},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzAzLzA5LzEzL2hlYWx0aGRhdGF2LjQ5YTQyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTk1MHg1MzQjCmUJanBn/1cf671d9/d62/health-data-viz.jpg","feature_image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzAzLzA5LzEzL2hlYWx0aGRhdGF2LjQ5YTQyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTE0Mzh4CmUJanBn/fd931bea/d62/health-data-viz.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzAzLzA5LzEzL2hlYWx0aGRhdGF2LjQ5YTQyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTIwMHgxMTUjCmUJanBn/9d4a62fe/d62/health-data-viz.jpg","query":true,"size":"200x115#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzAzLzA5LzEzL2hlYWx0aGRhdGF2LjQ5YTQyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTQwMHgyMzAjCmUJanBn/bad27a62/d62/health-data-viz.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"400x230#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1EJfUUa","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2014/11/29/social-good-innovations-2014/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"How fast did Ebola spread in Sierra Leone? How prevalent is obesity in the United States?","channel":"World","channel_label":"World","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/world/"},{"_id":"54f8840997b2f81c2900182a","id":"2015/03/05/last-ebola-patient-liberia","title":"Last Ebola patient in Liberia can go home","title_tag":null,"author":"The Associated Press","post_date":"2015-03-05T16:27:44+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Thu, 05 Mar 2015 16:27:44 +0000","sort_key":"1ytyCI","link":"http://mashable.com/2015/03/05/last-ebola-patient-liberia/","content":{"plain":"MONROVIA, Liberia \u2014 Liberia released its last Ebola patient, a 58-year old teacher, from a treatment center in the capital on Thursday, beginning its countdown to being declared Ebola free.\n\n\"I am one of the happiest human beings today on earth because it was not easy going through this situation and coming out alive,\" Beatrice Yardolo told The Associated Press after her release. She kept thanking God and the health workers at the center.\n\nSee also: Eyewitness to Hell: Life in Ebola-Ravaged Liberia\n\nYardolo said she had been admitted to the Chinese-run Ebola treatment center in the Paynesville district of Monrovia on Feb. 18. A mother of five, she is originally from the northeastern county of Nimba near the borders with Guinea and Ivory Coast, but lives in Monrovia where she teaches at a church-run school. The St. Paul's Bridge community where she resides and teaches had become the last \"hotspot\" for Ebola cases in Monrovia, according to Tolbert Nyenswah, Assistant Health Minister and head of the country's Ebola response.\n\nThere are no other confirmed cases of Ebola in the country, and as such Liberia can begin to count up to 42 days to be declared Ebola free in keeping with World Health Organization protocols and standards, Nyenswah said Wednesday. He challenged all Liberians to commit themselves to achieving \"zero Ebola infections\" by rigidly abiding by the anti-Ebola regulations.\n\nLiberian President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf has said no country can be declared Ebola free until all the other countries have no cases.\n\nSierra Leone, Liberia and Guinea have been hardest hit in the yearlong Ebola outbreak, which is estimated to have left more than 9,800 people dead.\n\nThe WHO on Wednesday reported 132 new Ebola cases last week, an increase from the 99 cases reported the previous week. The agency said the spread of Ebola remains \"widespread\" in Sierra Leone and noted that cases have jumped both there and in Guinea.\n\nNine new cases were reported in a 24-hour period, according to an update from the Sierra Leone government on Tuesday.\n\nWHO said only about half of new Ebola patients in Guinea are connected to known cases, meaning that health officials are unable to track where the disease is spreading in the other half of cases.\n\nThe U.N. health agency has said it will start large-scale testing of an experimental Ebola vaccine in Guinea on Saturday to see how effective it might be in preventing future outbreaks of the deadly virus.\n\nThe health agency's vaccination strategy in Guinea aims to create a buffer zone around an Ebola case to prevent its further spread. Officials will vaccinate people who have already been exposed to Ebola cases and are at risk of developing the disease.\n\nThe vaccine being tested \u2014 VSV-EBOV \u2014 was developed by Canada and is now licensed to Merck. A second vaccine \u2014 one developed by U.S. National Institutes of Health and GlaxoSmithKline \u2014 will be tested in a separate study as supplies become available.\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"twitter":483,"facebook":96,"pinterest":1,"total":580},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzAzLzA4LzRhL2xpYmVyaWFlYm9sLmYzYWFlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTk1MHg1MzQjCmUJanBn/04948654/477/liberia-ebola.jpg","feature_image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzAzLzA4LzRhL2xpYmVyaWFlYm9sLmYzYWFlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTE0Mzh4CmUJanBn/a7575ef2/477/liberia-ebola.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzAzLzA4LzRhL2xpYmVyaWFlYm9sLmYzYWFlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTIwMHgxMTUjCmUJanBn/96bd71dc/477/liberia-ebola.jpg","query":true,"size":"200x115#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzAzLzA4LzRhL2xpYmVyaWFlYm9sLmYzYWFlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTQwMHgyMzAjCmUJanBn/f79ac60c/477/liberia-ebola.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"400x230#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1H02aUE","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2014/10/24/ebola-liberia-hell-photographer/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"Liberia can now begin to count up to 42 days to be declared Ebola free.","channel":"World","chan